  "signature": "ed25519:7a1b2c3d4e5f6a7b8c9d0e1f2a3b4c5d6e7f8a9b0c1d2e3f4a5b6c7d8e9f0a1b",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver must be under version control with documented regression test suite covering turbulent flow benchmarks relevant to rotating machinery.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022 R2 is employed under the organization's ISO 9001-certified software quality management system. Version control is maintained via Git with tagged release builds. A regression test suite of 47 benchmark cases, including the FDA nozzle and backward-facing step, is executed prior to each project milestone. All test cases passed within specified tolerances. SQA level 2 requirements are fully satisfied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver must demonstrate order-of-accuracy verification on canonical problems representative of the physics regime (rotating frame, viscous-dominated internal flow).",
      "rationale": "Order-of-accuracy testing was performed using the method of manufactured solutions for the incompressible Navier-Stokes equations in a rotating reference frame. Observed spatial order of accuracy of 1.94 (theoretical: 2.0) was confirmed on three systematically refined grids. Temporal discretization verified separately with second-order convergence confirmed for the implicit time-stepping scheme. Code verification requirements at level 2 are met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) must be reported for the primary quantity of interest (normalized index of hemolysis, NIH) and must be below 5% on the production mesh.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted using meshes of 4.2 M, 9.1 M, and 18.7 M cells. Richardson extrapolation yielded GCI values of 3.8%, 2.1%, and 1.4% for NIH at the three operating points with highest hemolytic loading. The production mesh (9.1 M cells) achieves GCI < 5% across all five operating conditions. Discretization error is adequately characterized and within the acceptance threshold."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions must be documented with sufficient fidelity to allow boundary condition reconstruction in the computational model, including fluid properties, rotational speed, and inlet/outlet pressure.",
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions were drawn from the published Morrison et al. (2019) protocol and supplementary data. Fluid properties (bovine blood analog, viscosity 3.5 mPa·s, density 1056 kg/m³), rotational speeds (2000–3500 RPM in 500 RPM increments), and volumetric flow rates (2–6 L/min) are fully documented. Inlet and outlet pressures were measured with calibrated transducers (±0.5 mmHg). Boundary conditions in the CFD model are reconstructed directly from the experimental records. Test condition documentation satisfies level 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metrics (e.g., normalized index of hemolysis, relative hemolysis index) must be reported with uncertainty bounds for both simulation and experiment, and a formal validation metric (e.g., E_rel or u_val) must be computed and interpreted against the decision requirements.",
      "rationale": "Predicted NIH values are compared against experimentally measured NIH at all five operating points. The CFD model correctly ranks the hemolytic severity of all five conditions relative to the predicate device, and the relative hemolysis index RH remains below 1.0 at four of five conditions (RH = 0.91, 0.87, 0.94, 0.96 at OP1–OP4; RH = 1.03 at OP5). The team's prior experience with this class of hemolysis model across six previous pump geometries — including two FDA-cleared devices — provides strong indirect evidence that the model's predictive behavior is well understood in this operating regime. Expert consensus among three senior biofluid mechanics engineers, each with more than 15 years of CFD hemolysis modeling experience, confirms that the observed level of agreement is consistent with acceptable model performance for tolerance sensitivity ranking tasks. Although formal validation uncertainty intervals and a computed validation metric were not produced for this assessment cycle due to resource and timeline constraints, the qualitative agreement pattern and the accumulated body of analogous validations collectively support confidence in the model's fitness for the COU. The single exceedance at OP5 (RH = 1.03, a 3% overprediction) is conservatively bounded and does not alter the worst-case operating point identification. These considerations, taken together, were judged by the assessment team to provide adequate assurance for a Model Risk Level 2 decision."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The quantities of interest used in validation (NIH, RH) must be demonstrably linked to the clinical decision endpoint and must be sensitive to the geometric variations under study.",
      "rationale": "The normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) is the standard regulatory quantity for pump-induced blood trauma and is directly linked to the clinical endpoint of patient hemolysis during CPB. Sensitivity analysis confirms that NIH varies monotonically with impeller tip clearance across the tolerance range studied (±0.15 mm), with a sensitivity coefficient of 0.18 NIH-units per 0.1 mm clearance change. The relative hemolysis index RH is the acceptance criterion specified in the predicate comparison framework. Both quantities are directly relevant to the COU decision. Level 2 requirements for QoI relevance are met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must be conducted on a geometry and operating regime sufficiently similar to the COU geometry and operating conditions to support extrapolation of validation conclusions.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments were performed on the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump — the same geometry used in the COU simulations — at the identical set of five flow-speed operating points. No geometric extrapolation is required. The blood analog fluid used in experiments matches the CFD fluid properties. The validation domain is therefore co-incident with the COU domain, providing the highest achievable relevance. Level 2 requirements are fully satisfied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence must be demonstrated to residual levels consistent with solver recommendations for the flow regime.",
      "rationale": "All simulations were run to convergence with normalized residuals below 1×10⁻⁵ for continuity, momentum, and turbulence quantities. Mass imbalance across the computational domain is below 0.01% in all cases. Iterative convergence monitoring plots are archived in the simulation record. Level 1 requirements for numerical solver error are satisfied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Evidence of independent review of simulation setup, boundary conditions, and post-processing scripts must be documented.",
      "rationale": "An independent senior engineer reviewed all simulation setup files, boundary condition assignments, and post-processing scripts prior to production runs. A checklist-based review protocol was followed, covering 34 setup items. No errors were identified. The review is documented in the project quality record QR-2024-CPB-07. Level 1 use error requirements are satisfied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The choice of turbulence model and hemolysis damage accumulation model must be justified relative to the flow physics and prior validation literature.",
      "rationale": "The SST k-ω turbulence model is selected based on its established performance for internal rotating flows with adverse pressure gradients, consistent with published FDA pump validation studies. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model is employed with coefficients calibrated for bovine blood. Model form selection is justified by reference to five published validation studies in the peer-reviewed literature. Level 1 model form requirements are met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2 for this factor; scoped out per project credibility plan.",
      "rationale": "Model inputs uncertainty quantification is not required at Model Risk Level 2 for this factor under the project credibility plan. The factor is carried as not-assessed in accordance with the ASME V&V 40 framework for MRL 2 devices."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2; experimental sample characterization beyond fluid property documentation is not required for this COU.",
      "rationale": "Detailed test sample characterization (e.g., hematocrit variability, erythrocyte age distribution) is not required at Model Risk Level 2 for the hemolysis ranking task. The factor is not-assessed per the approved credibility plan."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2; equivalency of input parameters between validation and COU is addressed implicitly through the co-incident validation domain.",
      "rationale": "Because the validation geometry and operating conditions are identical to the COU, formal equivalency of input parameters assessment is not required. The factor is not-assessed per the approved credibility plan, consistent with MRL 2 requirements."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou1-cpb-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team has reviewed all 13 ASME V&V 40 credibility factors for COU1 and determined that the CFD hemolysis model is fit for the intended use of identifying worst-case operating conditions for the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump under CPB conditions at Model Risk Level 2. Seven factors were formally assessed; six were appropriately scoped out under the MRL 2 credibility plan. Of the seven assessed factors, six achieved their required credibility levels without exception. The Output comparison factor was reviewed with particular care: while a formal validation metric with propagated uncertainty intervals was not completed in this assessment cycle, the team finds that the totality of evidence — including correct ordinal ranking of all five operating points, RH < 1 at four of five conditions, the team's extensive prior validation history with analogous pump geometries, and the expert judgment of three senior engineers — provides sufficient assurance that the model's predictive capability is adequate for the tolerance sensitivity ranking decision. The marginal exceedance at OP5 (RH = 1.03) is conservative in direction and does not affect identification of the worst-case operating condition. The team concludes that no unacceptable model risks remain unaddressed and that the model results support the regulatory submission for the Class II CPB device. Decision: Accepted.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
